		<asp:Panel runat="server" ID="pnlGb" Visible="false" Width="100%">
			The seven levels of difficulty of the figure can be varied in numerous ways. For
			each level of difficulty, there are suggestions for two different variations. Think
			of more yourself.
			<br />
			<ol type="A">
				<li>The square is lying in the middle and is aligned. The other blocks are lying side
					by side against the square. </li>
				<li>The square is lying in the middle and is aligned. At least one of the other blocks
					is lying decentralised in relation to the square, so that the sides are not placed
					alongside each other. </li>
				<li>The square is lying in the middle and is aligned. The rest of the blocks are placed
					in such a way that either a pocket (open hole) or a gap appears between them.&nbsp;</li>
				<li>The square is lying in the middle, but at an angle. The other blocks are lying side
					by side against the square. </li>
				<li>The square is lying in the middle, but at an angle. At least one of the other blocks
					are decentralised in relation to the square, so that the sides are not placed alongside
					each other. </li>
				<li>The square is lying in the middle, but at an angle. The rest of the blocks are placed
					in such way that either a pocket (open hole) or a gap appears between them. </li>
				<li>The square is lying in the middle, either
					aligned or at an angle. At least one of the other blocks is positioned so that there
					is some space between this and the square. </li>
			</ol>
			<p>
				Should you wish to raise the level any
					further, you could do the abovementioned variations with the diamond or the triangle
					instead of the square. 
			</p>
